\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces PocketDRS three-tier system architecture: Flutter mobile client, FastAPI backend, and Firebase data/auth tier.}}{12}{figure.caption.1}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Mobile UI screens: pitch calibration with tap-to-mark corners (left), live analysis progress (centre), and server/runtime settings (right).}}{13}{figure.caption.2}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Result screen showing the reconstructed 3D trajectory in the Three.js viewer (left) and the LBW decision banner with reasoning (right).}}{14}{figure.caption.3}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Three.js Hawk-Eye viewer renders for two synthetic scenarios. Left: a medium-pace, middle-stump delivery producing an OUT verdict. Right: a delivery pitched wide of off, returning NOT OUT. The cyan/blue line is the recovered ball trajectory; the orange line (when present) is the projectile extrapolated forward to the stump plane.}}{24}{figure.caption.4}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Side-on view of a recovered trajectory: ball release at the bowler end (right), parabolic descent to the pitch, bounce, post-bounce arc, and impact in front of the striker stumps (left).}}{24}{figure.caption.5}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Real-world test footage: opening frame from the bowler-end stumps (left) and mid-delivery action (right). The pipeline ran end-to-end on this clip and produced an OUT decision.}}{25}{figure.caption.6}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Real-video diagnostics. Left: the manually-tapped pitch polygon overlaid on frame 0. Right: every per-frame ``ball'' detection drawn on a single frame, showing all 174 detections cluster within a $2.5 \times 97.5$ pixel region. The detector locked onto a stationary red/brown object near the batter rather than the moving cricket ball, because the source clip is a social-media reel with cuts rather than a continuous umpire-POV delivery shot.}}{26}{figure.caption.7}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Three.js render of the trajectory recovered from the real practice-nets video. The OUT verdict is displayed; the rendered trajectory collapses to a near-vertical column because the visually marked pitch corners produced a high-reprojection-error calibration, illustrating why precise tap calibration is required in production use.}}{27}{figure.caption.8}%
